<TITLE> Salahuddin BFF's new boss </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, April 28 (bdnews24.com)  Former football superstar Kazi Salahuddin has been elected president of Bangladesh Football Federation, edging out retired major general Amin Ahmed Chowdhury in the much-anticipated election at the BFF House in Arambagh Monday, according to official results. Salahuddin bagged 62 votes and Amin trailed behind with 49 as one vote was cancelled out of the 112 votes cast. "I am very happy as the councillors gave me a chance what I wanted from them this time," said Salahuddin in his instant reaction to the election to a four-year term. Amin congratulated Salahuddin on the win. The Amin-led combined panel won 11 seats on the 21-member executive committee while the Salahuddin-led 'like-minded' panel ended up with the remaining 10. The combined panel won four key postsone of senior vice-president and three of vice president along with seven members out of 15 while the like-minded panel won two key posts of president and vice-president. Former national striker Salam Murshidi beat Monir Ahmed 74 to 37 to be elected senior vice president from the combined panel. The panel also saw three vice presidents: Badal Roy and Shawkat Ali Khan Jahangir won the same number of votes62, and Kazi Nabil Ahmed bagged 58. The like-minded panel roped in Manzoor Hossain Malu, who secured 67 votes, the highest number as one of the four vice presidents. Eight former national footballers were elected in a remarkable feat of Monday's election, with Sheikh Mohammad Aslam bagging 79, the highest number of votes as member. Voting began at 2pm and continued through to 6.15pm with hundreds of followers of both panels waiting eagerly outside the BFF House as no-one was allowed in until the vote count completed shortly after 10:30pm. Before the voting, outgoing BFF president SA Sultan chaired the federation's annual general meeting, his last. Members of the Amin-led panel: Harun-or-Rashid, M Fazlur Rahman Babul, Sheikh Mohammad Aslam, Alhaj Shamsul Haq Chowdhury, Satyajit Das Rupu, M Hasanuzzaman Khan Babul and M Khurshid Alam Babul. Members of the Salahuddin-led group: Anwarul Haq Helal, Sirajul Islam Bachchu, Golam Rabbani Helal, Amirul Islam Babu, Alhaj Mokbul Hossain, Asfaruzzaman Suhrab, Mahbubur Rahman Shahin and Shafiquzzaman. bdnew
